posts.raw_content:
After listening to Tucker's interview with Nick Fuentes I have revised my opinion of Fuentes. 

I no longer think he is a closet faggot or a fed.
He seems like a pretty sincere America First conservative.
I do think that he really missed out by dropping out of college. Not that he needed indoctrination. It's just that while he's obviously smart and well read, he's a little too settled in his opinion. He doesn't seem like someone who's ever had to reconsider his opinions, not because he was proven wrong, but because there were deeper levels to the subject. He's kind of stunted in a high school like mindset, the teenager who 'knows everything'. It's kind of a mask to cover his insecurities.

You see it best when Tucker asks him why he attacks people who are the most America First, like Joe Kent or MTG. Fuente's answer is always a variant of "They attacked me first" as if it were some sort of spat between siblings in the back seat.

You see it again when Fuentes talks about women, as 'simple' and then admits he's not in a relationship. You get the feeling that he's one of those virgin sex experts.

All of that said, Fuentes comes off as genuine and likable. Hardly a monster. For the first time I heard about the assassination attempt against him.

A measure of how reasonable Fuentes is, he doesn't think it was the Joos or the deep state that sent the assassin. Instead he thinks it was the assassin being caught up in an unreal online world while have his IRL world collapse that led him there. This becomes a segue into a discussion of how people are attempting to escape reality through Marijuana, porn and ultra-niche online communities.

Worth a listen if you don't know Fuentes.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=efBB0D4tf1Y
